[src:billy-herman/1931-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1931 throughout the world.
[src:billy-herman/1931-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:billy-herman/1931-in-baseball] This was the twelfth and final season of the original Negro National League.
[src:billy-herman/1931-in-baseball] The season did not finish all games, which meant that while St.
[src:billy-herman/1931-in-baseball] Louis was awarded the title, non-member Pittsburgh Crawford Giants disputed their status as champion.
[src:billy-herman/1931-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams were gathered in the East to compete with the West, however East teams did not organize a formal league as the West did.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The **1931 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1931.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 27, with the St.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and Philadelphia Athletics as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 28th World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 7 on October 10.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), the Cardinals defeated the Athletics, four games to three, capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1926.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1930 season.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA) selected a Most Valuable Player in each league.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The 1931 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 14, featured all sixteen teams, the first time since the 1926 season.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 27, which also saw all sixteen teams play on the final day continuing the trend which began the previous season.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first time that both Opening Day and the final day of the season saw all sixteen teams play.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 1 and October 10.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] 9 tie games (5 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 10 with the St.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals defeating the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1931 World Series in seven games.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] Across 80 homes games, the Boston Red Sox played all 15 of their Sunday games at the Boston Braves home field of Braves Field (the remaining 65 home games were played at Fenway Park).
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of three consecutive seasons playing all Sunday games at Braves Field and 3rd of four consecutive season playing some games at Braves Field.
[src:billy-herman/1931-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of 31 consecutive seasons that the Cleveland Indians played at their inaugural field, League Park (they would play full seasons at the Park in 1934 and 1935, while 1932, and 1936 to 1946 saw home games split with Cleveland Stadium.
[src:billy-herman/1932-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1932 throughout the world.
[src:billy-herman/1932-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:billy-herman/1932-in-baseball] 1932 was the only time the Negro Southern League was considered a major league.
[src:billy-herman/1932-in-baseball] Chicago won the first half while Nashville won the second half.
[src:billy-herman/1932-in-baseball] They matched up against each other in a best-of-seven postseason series, which Chicago won four to three.
[src:billy-herman/1932-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams existed that were not part of either established leagues.
[src:billy-herman/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1934 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the second edition of the mid-summer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:billy-herman/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] It was held on July 10 in Manhattan, New York City, at the Polo Grounds, the home of the New York Giants of the National League, the defending World Series champions.
[src:billy-herman/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League won 9–7, and every starter on both teams except Wally Berger was later inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:billy-herman/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game is well known among baseball historians for the performance of NL starting pitcher Carl Hubbell of the host Giants.
[src:billy-herman/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] After allowing the first two batters to reach base on a single and a base on balls, Hubbell struck out five of the game's best hitters – Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Jimmie Foxx, Al Simmons, and Joe Cronin – in succession, setting a longstanding All-Star Game record for consecutive strikeouts.
[src:billy-herman/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Trailing 4–2, the American League scored six times in the top of the fifth inning to take the lead for good.
[src:billy-herman/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The teams combined for sixteen runs on 22 hits; the two home runs were hit early in the game by the NL (Frankie Frisch, Joe Medwick), both with the St.
[src:billy-herman/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis Cardinals, the World Series champions later that year.
[src:billy-herman/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Players in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:billy-herman/1934-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Cy Pfirman, NL (home), Brick Owens, AL (first base), Dolly Stark, NL (second base), George Moriarty, AL (third base); the umpires rotated positions clockwise in the middle of the fifth inning, with Owens moving behind the plate.
