[src:billy-herman/1935-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per Seamheads.
[src:billy-herman/1935-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams existed that were not part of the Negro National League.
[src:billy-herman/1936-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1936 throughout the world.
[src:billy-herman/1938-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1938 throughout the world.
[src:billy-herman/1938-in-baseball] Memphis beat Atlanta 2 games to 0 games in a contested play-off.
[src:billy-herman/1938-in-baseball] At the league's winter meetings it was decided that the Red Sox had won the Negro American League pennant due to Memphis' two wins and the forfeiture of Atlanta in game three of the series.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Born in New Albany, Indiana, in 1909, and named after William Jennings Bryan, the three-time presidential candidate and statesman of the turn of the 20th century, Herman attended New Albany High School.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Herman broke into the majors in 1931 with the Chicago Cubs and asserted himself as a star the following season, 1932, by hitting .314 and scoring 102 runs.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Facing Cincinnati Reds pitcher Si Johnson, Herman chopped a pitch into the back of home plate, which then bounced up and hit Herman in the back of the head, knocking him out.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] A fixture in the Chicago lineup over the next decade, Herman was a consistent hitter and solid producer.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] He regularly hit .300 or higher (and as high as .341 in 1935) and drove in a high of 93 runs in 1936.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] He also hit 57 doubles in both 1935 and 1936.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] After a sub-standard offensive year in 1940, Herman was traded to the Brooklyn Dodgers in 1941.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] He had one of his finest offensive season in 1943, when he batted .330 with a .398 on-base percentage and 100 runs driven in.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Herman missed the 1944 and 1945 seasons to serve in World War II, but returned to play in 1946 with the Dodgers and Boston Braves (after being traded mid-season).
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] At 37, he was considered prime managerial material by the new owners of the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] On September 30, 1946, Herman was traded to Pittsburgh with three marginal players (outfielder Stan Wentzel, pitcher Elmer Singleton and infielder Whitey Wietelmann) for third baseman Bob Elliott and catcher Hank Camelli.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Herman was promptly named playing manager of the 1947 Pirates, but he was aghast at the cost—Elliott—the Pirates had paid for him.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] "Why, they've gone and traded the whole team on me", he said.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Elliott won the 1947 NL Most Valuable Player award and led Boston to the 1948 National League pennant.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Herman's 1947 Pirates lost 92 games and finished tied for seventh in the NL, and he resigned before the season's final game.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Herman then managed in the minor leagues and became a Major League coach with the Dodgers (1952–57) and Braves (now based in Milwaukee) (1958–59)—serving on five National League pennant winners in eight seasons.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Then he moved to the American League (AL) as the third-base coach of the Boston Red Sox for five years (1960–64), before managing the Red Sox to lackluster records in 1965 and 1966; his 1965 Boston club lost 100 games.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] After his firing by the Red Sox in September 1966, he coached for the California Angels (1967) and San Diego Padres (1978–79) and served in player development roles with the Padres and Oakland Athletics.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Herman finished his 1,922-game big-league career with a .304 batting average, 1,163 runs scored, 2,345 hits, 486 doubles, 82 triples, 47 home runs, 839 runs batted in, 737 bases on balls and 428 strikeouts.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Defensively, he recorded an overall .968 fielding percentage.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] He won four NL pennants (1932, 1935, 1938, and 1941) but no World Series championships as a player (although he was a coach on the 1955 World Series champion Brooklyn Dodgers).
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] His record as a Major League manager was 189-274 (.408).
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Herman holds the NL records for most putouts in a season by a second baseman and led the league in putouts seven times.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] He also shares the Major League record for most hits on opening day, with five, set April 14, 1936.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Herman moved to Palm Beach Gardens, Florida in 1968.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] He was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1975.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] In 2013, the Bob Feller Act of Valor Award honored Herman as one of 37 Baseball Hall of Fame members for his service in the United States Navy during World War II.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] According to his honorable discharge, he was awarded the American Campaign Medal, the Asiatic Pacific Campaign Medal, and the WWII Victory Medal.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] He held the rank of Specialist (A) Third Class at the time of his separation.
[src:billy-herman/billy-herman] Herman's granddaughter is Cheri Herman Daniels, wife of former Indiana Governor Mitch Daniels.
